Data Visualization With ggplot2

Andrew Bates

11/29/2018

Welcome

In this workshop we will be visualizing data using the R package ggplot2. From the package website:

ggplot2 is a system for declaratively creating graphics, based on The Grammar of Graphics. You provide the data, tell ggplot2 how to map variables to aesthetics, what graphical primitives to use, and it takes care of the details.

We will talk more about what this means so dont worry if this doesnt make sense yet. If youve been to the previous workshops I did, this one will be quite a bit different. It will be more interactive and we will be updating this document as we go. I will demonstrate how to make a couple of simple plots, then I will get your input and we will make some plots together.

What Makes a Plot?

Before we start actually building plots, lets take a few minutes to think about what goes into a plot. Consider the following plot.

What are the components that go into this plot? If we had to build this up piece by piece, what would the pieces be?

  • component 1
  • component 2
  • component 4

This plot was made with one of the data sets that comes with ggplot2. The data set has information on fuel economy for cars from 1999-2008. The code to generate the plot is:

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Displacement",
       y = "Highway MPG",
       color = "Class")

A First Plot

Now that we have an idea of what some of the pieces of a plot are, lets make some of our own. We will be using data on NCAA mens basketball teams from the 2017-2018 season. The data was collected from sports-reference.com. Lets start by loading some packages and reading in the data. Dont worry about the here package if you havent seen it before. ggplot2 is part of the tidyverse so we can load it by loading the tidyverse package. There are a few other tidyverse pacakges we will use which is why we laod tidyverse instead of just ggplot2. You dont need to worry about the other packages though. Just focus on the ggplot2 parts.

library(here)
library(tidyverse)
bball <- read_csv(here("fall_18", "data", "ncaa-basketball-17-18.csv"))

Lets make a bar chart that displays the number of wins for each team. We will plot the number of wins on the y axis and the school name on the x axis. There are 351 teams in the data set. Putting them all on the same plot will be a bit overwhelming so lets just look at the CSU and UC schools. We start by creating a new data frame with only these schools. Again, you dont need to worry about how this is done, just know thats what we are doing.

csuc <- bball %>% 
  filter(str_detect(school, "Cal State") | 
           str_detect(school, "San Diego State") |
           str_detect(school, "UC"))


ggplot(csuc, aes(x = school, y = wins)) +
  geom_col()

This isnt so great. Lets rotate the names so we can read them and make the bars red and black for SDSU.

ggplot(csuc, aes(x = school, y = wins)) +
  geom_col(fill = "black", color = "red") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
